issues.body:
While reviewing the following structures, I noticed a potential ambiguity around the flexible array members:
```
struct sctp_dtls_kmids {
        sctp_assoc_t sdk_assoc_id;
        uint16_t sdk_nr_kmids;
        uint16_t sdk_kmids[];
};

struct sctp_dtls_keys {
        sctp_assoc_t sdk_assoc_id;
        uint8_t sdk_cipher_suite[2];
        uint8_t sdk_restart;
        uint8_t sdk_unused; /* if sizeof(sctp_assoc_t) == 4 */
        uint64_t sdk_epoch;
        uint16_t sdk_key_len;
        uint16_t sdk_iv_len;
        uint16_t sdk_sn_key_len;
        uint8_t sdk_keys[];
};
```

For example, given `struct sctp_dtls_kmids *kmids = BIG_BUF;`, The flexible array may be accessed as:

`kmids->sdk_kmids;`

`(uint8_t *)kmids + sizeof(*kmids);` or `(uint8_t *)(kmids + 1)`

In many cases these are expected to point to the same location, but with the current layout this is not guaranteed because there is no explicit padding before the flexible array. As a result, the offset computed using sizeof(struct) may differ from the actual start of the array.

One possible improvement would be to introduce explicit padding/unused fields or adjust field sizes so that the layout is unambiguous. For example:

```
struct sctp_dtls_kmids {
        sctp_assoc_t sdk_assoc_id;
        uint16_t sdk_unused;
        uint16_t sdk_nr_kmids;
        uint16_t sdk_kmids[];
};

struct sctp_dtls_keys {
        sctp_assoc_t sdk_assoc_id;
        uint8_t sdk_cipher_suite[2];
        uint8_t sdk_restart;
        uint8_t sdk_unused; /* if sizeof(sctp_assoc_t) == 4 */
        uint64_t sdk_epoch;
        uint16_t sdk_unused;
        uint16_t sdk_key_len;
        uint16_t sdk_iv_len;
        uint16_t sdk_sn_key_len;
        uint8_t sdk_keys[];
};
```
Or, sdk_nr_kmids in sctp_dtls_kmids could be changed to uint32_t to naturally align the structure.

comments.body:
> What is the alignment requirement of `uint16_t sdk_kmids[]`? I thought it is 16-bit, not 32-bit. Am I missing something?

This is not the problem.

The problem is:

`kmids->sdk_kmids` and `(uint8_t *)(kmids + 1)` are pointing to the different memory?

is it okay to you?

When packing or parsing the kmids at the end of `struct sctp_dtls_kmids`, I think some users may use `kmids->sdk_kmids` and others may use `(uint8_t *)(kmids + 1)`.

```
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stdio.h>

struct sctp_dtls_kmids {
	uint32_t sdk_assoc_id;
	uint16_t sdk_nr_kmids;
	uint16_t sdk_kmids[];
};

int main()
{
	struct sctp_dtls_kmids *kmids;
	uint8_t buf[100];

	kmids = (struct sctp_dtls_kmids *)buf;

	printf("%p %p\n", kmids->sdk_kmids, (uint8_t *)(kmids + 1));
}
```

@ValorZard first of all this is not at all for WebRTC. WebRTC uses SCTP over DTLS over UDP/IP. This draft is for securing SCTP over IP. The primary target for this is 3GPP's use of SCTP as transport protocol for its control plane signalling. Clearly also usable for any other SCTP usage as the security solution is integrated into SCTP.

Thus, SNAP will not be relevant at all as the layering that SNAP tries to accelerate does not exist in this protocol. However, I do note that where SNAP tries to parallelize the SCTP handshake with DTLS, DTLS Chunk requires a key management handshake after the SCTP handshake.  

In fact adopting a DTLS Chunk based security solution into WebRTC would mean that one would need to run IP/UDP/SCTP instead of IP/UDP/DTLS/SCTP. Which would mean that one would attempt to multiple STUN, RTP, DTLS-SRTP, and SCTP on the first byte of the UDP payload. That would mean that one would be forced to select SCTP source port numbers such that it could multiplex with the other protocols. Clearly possible but I would think such a large change for really no gain is of no ones interest.

